	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Call for fundamental review of the EAC CET</h1>

			
			<h4>
												04 November 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A member of the Trade and Investment Committee of the East African Business Council, writing in the press in September 2012, has called for the EAC’s common external tariff (CET) to be reviewed. The protocol agreed in 2005 on the CET to be applied by EAC customs union members was based on three tariff bands:</p>
<ul>

<li>primary raw materials; </li>

<li>industrial inputs; </li>

<li>capital equipment or finished goods. </li>

</ul>
<p>However, it also included:</p>
<ul>

<li>country-specific lists of exceptions to the CET; </li>

<li>duty remission schemes; </li>

<li>accommodation of trade agreements with third parties; </li>

<li>discretionary actions by partner governments. </li>

</ul>
<p>It was implicit that these exceptions ‘would operate side by side with the gradual elimination of internal tariffs and expire with the realisation of a fully-fledged Customs Union’. Uganda subsequently negotiated an extension of the operation of its country list of exceptions, while Rwanda and Burundi included their own exception lists when acceding to the EAC Customs Union. Over time, ‘discretionary action by some states has contributed to erosion of the CET’.</p><p>The author suggests that the list of derogations has become so long that ‘the current CET exists only in book form as each country is now operating its own external tariff albeit with substantial similarity with those of other partner states.’ In addition, many ‘para-tariff measures’ (e.g. import fees and levies) are applied at national level.</p><p>The author has therefore called on the EAC Sectoral Committee on Finance and Fiscal Affairs to ‘go back to the drawing board and prioritise review’ of the EAC CET regime, including the extensive system of exceptions, in order to ensure the application of a harmonised CET across the EAC. A similar call was made by representatives of the East African Chamber of Commerce and Industry at the beginning of October 2012.</p><p>The UN Economic Commission for Africa (UNECA), meanwhile, has highlighted the importance of addressing non-tariff barriers to trade through trade facilitation measures, through the contribution of a speaker to the Africa Trade Forum held in September in Addis Ababa. Several possible actions were identified that could reduce business costs. For example:</p>
<ul>

<li>establishing one-stop border posts ‘could reduce trade costs by about 2.4 per cent’;</li>

<li>implementing best practices on management of information and providing advance rulings on tariffs and duties could ‘reduce the trade costs by at least 5.5 per cent’; </li>

<li>‘streamlining fees could cut 1.7 per cent of total costs’. </li>

</ul>
<p>The UNECA Director for the Regional Integration and Trade Division also highlighted how cutting 10% off trade costs ‘means a lot to the bottom-line and the competitive margin’ of companies.</p><p>The EAC and African Union Commission have recently published a series of joint reports assessing regional integration in Africa.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Standard Digital</i> (Kenya), ‘There’s need to review EAC’s common external tariff’, 17 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.trademarksa.org/news/there-s-need-review-eac-s-common-external-tariff" target="_self">http://www.trademarksa.org/news/there-s-need-review-eac-s-common-externa...</a></p><p>UNECA, ‘ECA’s Karingi: Remove trade barriers and scale up good practices’, 26 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.trademarksa.org/news/eca-s-karingi-remove-trade-barriers-and-scale-good-practices" target="_self">http://www.trademarksa.org/news/eca-s-karingi-remove-trade-barriers-and-...</a></p><p>UN Economic Commission for Africa, ‘Assessing Regional Integration in Africa’, 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://new.uneca.org/aria/aria5.aspx" target="_self">http://new.uneca.org/aria/aria5.aspx</a></p><p><i>African Business Review</i>, ‘Red tape slows inter-state trade in East Africa’, 3 October 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/10/03/red-tape-slows-inter-state-trade-in-east-africa/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/10/03/red-tape-slows-inter-state-trade-in-eas...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>One of the fundamental issues in the EAC CET that requires clarification is the definition of the three tariff bands: a comprehensive and consistent review is required of which products fall into which band. Current arrangements provide for discretionary measures and an extensive list of exemptions, the overall effect of which is to undermine the integrity of the process of creating a single CET for all products. This is particularly the case in the food and agricultural sector, with a wide range of food and agricultural products no longer covered by the CET.</p><p>This problem arises not only in the EAC but also in the COMESA context. Efforts to tackle this issue at the EAC level thus carry wider implications for regional trade across Eastern and Southern Africa.</p><p>For example, the Zambia Dairy Processors Association has been against importation of milk powder that can be considered either as a final product (if for direct consumption) or an intermediate product (if the milk powder will be used to reconstitute milk or make ice-cream). In the case of reconstituted milk for direct consumption using imported milk powder, locally produced milk has been unable to compete on price, and hence calls have been made by local producers for a revision of duties on imported milk powder.</p><p>In the EAC, COMESA and wider tripartite FTA contexts, the questions arise:</p>
<ul>

<li>How can member states be obliged to implement what has been agreed upon, within the spirit of the creation of a single internal market?&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </li>

<li>What role should the private sector play in ensuring that the agreed CET is progressively implemented (since it is often specific private sector interests that lobby for exemptions and discretionary measures in the first place)?</li>

<li>What support measures should be set in place to incentivise fuller compliance with CET commitments (e.g. sector restructuring support)?</li>

</ul>
<p>Addressing these questions would lay a sounder basis for ensuring compliance with CET commitments, as well as for the creation of the larger markets required to encourage regional market-focused investments and more competitive forms of production.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
